post_text:
Families,
We are living in a rapidly evolving time with changes on how to maintain a safe and orderly environment for all of our students, staff, and families in Winthrop Harbor. It is with a heavy heart that I have decided to cancel school all next week and use them as our back-up emergency days. This will take us to our scheduled spring break during the week of March 23rd. We anticipate this short break will allow for better planning and time to understand the effects of the spread of the Coronavirus (COVID-19). The building principals will be following up with a letter to parents explaining how students may continue to learn using their Chromebooks.
We will send out further updates when they become available. I apologize for any inconveniences this may cause families, but we must continue to make student safety a priority.
Thank you,
Jeffrey McCartney
Superintendent of Schools
Winthrop Harbor School District #1

post_text: As a means of identifying preschool children who may qualify for special education services, Winthrop Harbor School District screens children in the areas of pre-academic learning concepts, motor skills, and communication. The screening team uses the Development Indicators for the Assessment of Learning- Fourth Edition (DIAL-4) to briefly assess children's developmental skills. If you suspect that your child is experiencing one or more delays in her or his development, please contact Westfield School to schedule a screen to be held on August 30th, 2019.

post_text: On January 24, 2013, Erin's Law was signed by Governor Pat Quinn. This law requires schools to implement an age-appropriate sexual assault and abuse awareness and prevention curriculum for grades pre-K through 12. We are pleased to share that Victor Pacini will be visiting our schools to deliver his program, Be Seen and Heard, a prevention-oriented child sexual abuse program. For more information about this presentation please view this short "PEACE OF MIND” video: http://www.victorpacini.com/peace-of-mind/ You can also check out Victor's Facebook page, Victor Pacini- Childhood Victories.

post_text:
Hello Winthrop Harbor parents and community members!

We wished to inform everyone that the Board of Education is conducting a search for a new superintendent. The selection of a new superintendent is probably the most important decision the Board has to make, therefore, the Board has hired the Illinois Association of School Boards (IASB) to assist them in this process.

At this point the Board is seeking input in the search process and has requested staff, parents, and community members to complete the online survey provided by the IASB. The results will be tallied and used by the Board and Screening Team to develop a brochure to advertise the position to the ideal candidate.

The survey can be accessed at our website under the Announcements section on the home page, or through the following direct link: www.surveymonkey.com/r/H627MSC

The deadline for completion is September 22, 2017 @ 11:59 PM.

Thank you for taking the time to complete the survey!
shared_text:
SURVEYMONKEY.COM
Winthrop Harbor SD 1 Superintendent Search Survey
text:
Hello Winthrop Harbor parents and community members!

We wished to inform everyone that the Board of Education is conducting a search for a new superintendent. The selection of a new superintendent is probably the most important decision the Board has to make, therefore, the Board has hired the Illinois Association of School Boards (IASB) to assist them in this process.

At this point the Board is seeking input in the search process and has requested staff, parents, and community members to complete the online survey provided by the IASB. The results will be tallied and used by the Board and Screening Team to develop a brochure to advertise the position to the ideal candidate.

The survey can be accessed at our website under the Announcements section on the home page, or through the following direct link: www.surveymonkey.com/r/H627MSC

The deadline for completion is September 22, 2017 @ 11:59 PM.

Thank you for taking the time to complete the survey!

WHSD Supporters,

Join Vigeo Exchange to earn money for WHSD Teacher Grants!

About 4 years ago the Winthrop Harbor Enrichment Endowment Fund was created. The Fund is governed by a Board with the sole goal of providing grant opportunities for Winthrop Harbor School District TEACHERS. The Foundation Board became a part of Vigeo Exchange funding opportunity. Basically, supporters sign up to be a Vigeo member (no cost). Once you became a member, you identify Winthrop Harbor Education Enrichment as your organization to profit. Then when you go to any businesses that are members, you tell them you are a Vigeo member and they credit you and the Foundation cash back (ranging from 2-15% of your… More

QUESTION: If the voters pass the bond question on the April 7 ballot, will my taxes be raised?

No. The current bonds that were used to build North Prairie will be expiring. If the bond question is affirmed, new bonds will be issued as the old ones expire, and there will be no resulting increase in bond taxes.

--
In an effort to make sure all residents of Winthrop Harbor are informed about the upcoming bond question on the April 7 ballot, the district is posting a series of frequently asked questions on the issue. More information can be found on the district's website at http://goo.gl/ZbwWUP.

QUESTION: How did the district determine the needs of the facilities?

Fanning and Howey, an architectural firm, completed a comprehensive facilities assessment and identified many needs over the next 20 years, and prioritized those needs based on urgency. A state funded energy assessment was conducted by SEDAC (Smart Energy Design Assessment Center) to identify ways to conserve and improve energy use in each building.

post_text:
Reading Tip of the Week: Puzzles Build Literacy Skills

Puzzles are a great way to help build early reading skills. Getting that puzzle piece in the right place takes some manipulation. Sometimes the piece is in the wrong place or just turned the wrong way. Flipping or rotating each piece in order to complete the puzzle helps develop children’s ability to problem-solve and think logically.

Working puzzles to make sure the pieces fit helps children understand that letters fit together to make words and words fit together to make sentences. Just like puzzle pieces, letters and words fit together to create the words and sentences we need to read and write.

Puzzles help children understand that a story has a beginning, middle, and end, much like a puzzle. When children work a puzzle, they have to start somewhere and then finish it. Many of us have a plan to complete it, just like all stories have a plan to get to an end.

Reading Tip of the Week: Winter Reading Challenge

Here are thirteen reading ideas to get you through the long, cold winter! Try to complete one each week:

1. A book with a color in the title
2. A book by an author whose last name starts with “w”
3. A non-fiction book about winter
4. A book about a winter sport
5. A book with a recipe (bonus points if you make the recipe!)
6. A multicultural book
7. The Caldecott winner (new winners will be announced 2/2/15)
8. A book about love, caring, or sharing
9. A book that is a song you can sing
10. Your favorite book from your own childhood
11. A Dr. Seuss book
12. A book that became a movie
13. Picture Book of the Day recommendation

http://growingbookbybook.com/2014/12/19/reading-activities-winter-reading-challenge/

Reading Tip of the Week: Research by Reading Level

The internet is an awesome resource for kids to use when researching. However, frequently the material is too difficult for some kids to read. Here's a great tip I recently learned that may help.

1. Go to www.google.com

2. Type in the topic you want to search.

3. Click on "Search Tools" and then the tab that says "All Results"

4. Click on "Reading Level" and the level that's appropriate for your child
